explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - the macro may have side-effects (logging, assertion, early return/abort). Its definition is needed to know whether its execution is essential or removable (dead) in this function.
OS_ObjectIdGetById - called to obtain a token and its return value gates the rest of the function; need its implementation/semantics to know if the call has observable side-effects beyond the return value (e.g. modifying global state, refcounts) so removal would change behaviour.
OS_ObjectIdRelease - releases the token; must know whether this call performs observable state changes (transaction finish, refcount decrement, resource cleanup). If it has effects then it is not dead.
OS_ShellOutputToFile_Impl - does the actual work when ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its side-effects (writing to file/stream, updating state) determine whether the call sequence is meaningful and thus not dead.
OS_SUCCESS - symbolic return used in the conditional; its value/semantics determine control flow. Understanding what constitutes success is required to judge whether subsequent operations are reachable/meaningful.
OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT / OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM - these argument macros/constants influence how ObjectIdGetById behaves (e.g. whether it changes refcounts or selects different object handling). Their definitions affect whether the call has side-effects and thus whether it can be considered dead.
OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit / OS_ObjectIdConvertToken / OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel / OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish / OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex - these helper functions are invoked (directly or indirectly) by OS_ObjectIdGetById / OS_ObjectIdRelease according to the call graph. Their implementations may perform the actual observable state changes (transactions, refcount manipulation, index conversions). To decide if the ObjectId* calls in the target are dead, their semantics must be known.
